In the first step we process β and construct a stack σR, which we call the right stack associated with c and tG. Each node of σR is the root of a tree t which satisfies the following properties
• t is a tree fragment of the gold tree tG having span entirely included in the buffer β;
• t is bottom-up complete for tG, meaning that for each node i of t different from t’s root, the dependents of i in tG cannot be in σL;
• t is maximal for tG, meaning that every supertree of t in tG violates the above conditions.
The stack σR is incrementally constructed by processig β from left to right. Each node i is copied into σR if it satisfies any of the following conditions
• the parent node of i in tG is not in β;
• some dependent of i in tG is in σL or has already been inserted in σR.
It is not difficult to see that the nodes in σR are the roots of tree fragments of tG that satisfy the condition of bottom-up completeness and the condition of maximality defined above.
